igating among varied possibilities for conceptualizing and enacting peoplehood in the context of continuing settler intervention. As Rifkin demonstrates, attending to writings by these Indigenous intellectuals provides ways of understanding Native governance as a matter of deliberation, discussion, and debate, emphasizing the open-ended unfinishedness of self-determination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIndians of North AmericaxColonization. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021636zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021636/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles